>> REGINA: --much a
generational divide on this one.

00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:34.025 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: It is.

00:01:34.025 --> 00:01:34.825 align:middle line:90%
It is.

00:01:34.825 --> 00:01:35.660 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: It is.

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:37.970 align:middle line:84%
So first of all,
everyone's saying sir?

00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:39.613 align:middle line:84%
But he doesn't have
a British accent.

00:01:39.613 --> 00:01:41.030 align:middle line:84%
How did you end
up being knighted?

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:42.947 align:middle line:10%
>> Shults: Well, it's
interesting because many

00:01:42.947 --> 00:01:46.400 align:middle line:10%
knighthoods are conferred
by other kings and domains.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:48.140 align:middle line:10%
King of Sweden,
the King of Denmark

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:50.270 align:middle line:10%
have knights in their
service, but it actually

00:01:50.270 --> 00:01:52.250 align:middle line:10%
came about because
I was knighted

00:01:52.250 --> 00:01:56.870 align:middle line:10%
by a Scottish Baron who
purchased the Leslie baronage.

00:01:56.870 --> 00:02:00.020 align:middle line:10%
And under the terms
of the Magna Carta,

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:02.420 align:middle line:10%
landed barons were
allowed to knight people,

00:02:02.420 --> 00:02:06.020 align:middle line:10%
and that was in 1215, and
it's not been repealed.

00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:09.440 align:middle line:84%
So I was awarded a five-year
grant and a knighthood

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:11.690 align:middle line:84%
to pursue my research in
artificial intelligence

00:02:11.690 --> 00:02:12.490 align:middle line:90%
and robotics.

00:02:12.490 --> 00:02:14.030 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well,
and you're here,

00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:16.413 align:middle line:84%
and you were able to do
that with that grant too.

00:02:16.413 --> 00:02:17.330 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Absolutely.

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:17.960 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Wonderful.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:20.180 align:middle line:84%
And I know you have a
splendid piece of property

00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:22.950 align:middle line:84%
where you're coming up
with all kinds of stuff.

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:24.840 align:middle line:84%
So we won't even get
into that just yet.

00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:28.670 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, we're
talking about brain implants.

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:32.190 align:middle line:84%
This is something that has
been rather frightening

00:02:32.190 --> 00:02:34.710 align:middle line:84%
for a lot of people,
especially people

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:38.910 align:middle line:84%
who frequent a lot of
conspiracy sites, in particular.

00:02:38.910 --> 00:02:42.450 align:middle line:84%
And I want to start
tearing down what

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:45.540 align:middle line:84%
we have reason to
be concerned about

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:47.820 align:middle line:84%
and what we have reason
to be excited about,

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:51.240 align:middle line:84%
because whether we like it
or not, AI is here to stay,

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:55.890 align:middle line:84%
and it's going to become
an increasingly more

00:02:55.890 --> 00:02:57.810 align:middle line:84%
prevalent part of our
lives on every level.

00:02:57.810 --> 00:02:58.755 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: It will.

00:02:58.755 --> 00:03:00.180 align:middle line:90%
It absolutely will.

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:02.230 align:middle line:84%
And as a lot of
people point out,

00:03:02.230 --> 00:03:05.310 align:middle line:84%
it's one of those technologies
that, like a video game

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:07.590 align:middle line:84%
or like instant
communications, is

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:10.775 align:middle line:84%
going to pervade our lives
at every level very soon.

00:03:10.775 --> 00:03:12.900 align:middle line:84%
So it's good to know where
we stand, what it means,

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:14.295 align:middle line:90%
and what it's all about.

00:03:14.295 --> 00:03:15.545 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: I absolutely agree.

00:03:15.545 --> 00:03:16.345 align:middle line:90%
Go ahead.

00:03:16.345 --> 00:03:17.820 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: So well,
to start with,

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:22.350 align:middle line:84%
a lot of the research lately
has been in an effort to open

00:03:22.350 --> 00:03:23.370 align:middle line:90%
the human mind.

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:25.800 align:middle line:84%
And the fact is,
the human mind has

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:28.830 align:middle line:84%
been locked away since the
beginning of humankind.

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:31.573 align:middle line:84%
And there's not an easy
communication-- well,

00:03:31.573 --> 00:03:32.490 align:middle line:90%
communication channel.

00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:34.470 align:middle line:84%
In and out of it
we speak, we draw,

00:03:34.470 --> 00:03:35.940 align:middle line:84%
we communicate
with other people,

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:37.650 align:middle line:90%
but that's a limited bandwidth.

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:39.420 align:middle line:90%
You can only share so much.

00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:42.390 align:middle line:84%
When we get down to the
ability to literally tap

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:45.955 align:middle line:84%
into the computers that
reside in the brain

00:03:45.955 --> 00:03:47.580 align:middle line:84%
and get information
in and out of them,

00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:49.800 align:middle line:84%
suddenly, we have
a huge expansion

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.090 align:middle line:90%
of what we're capable of.

00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:54.480 align:middle line:84%
Primarily right now, people are
looking at movement control,

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:57.570 align:middle line:84%
such as paralysis or
spinal cord injury, how

00:03:57.570 --> 00:03:59.430 align:middle line:84%
they can read the
signals out of the brain

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:03.270 align:middle line:84%
and bypass the damaged areas
and restore movement and control

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:04.150 align:middle line:90%
the people.

00:04:04.150 --> 00:04:05.145 align:middle line:90%
And that's a big plus.

00:04:05.145 --> 00:04:08.160 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah, and we're going
to go down that rabbit hole

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:10.410 align:middle line:84%
a little further because we
have a couple of different

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:11.620 align:middle line:90%
technologies out there.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:13.260 align:middle line:84%
One of them is Elon
Musk's Neuralink

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:14.760 align:middle line:84%
which frightens a
lot of people that

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:16.649 align:middle line:90%
are watching this right now.

00:04:16.649 --> 00:04:19.140 align:middle line:84%
But when you're talking
about opening the human mind,

00:04:19.140 --> 00:04:20.970 align:middle line:84%
there's a transcendental
element to that.

00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:22.440 align:middle line:90%
It's not just raw data in there.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:23.560 align:middle line:90%
It's capability, right?

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:24.360 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Right.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:25.170 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:04:25.170 --> 00:04:28.230 align:middle line:84%
And everybody shares
a lot of skills

00:04:28.230 --> 00:04:31.620 align:middle line:84%
that are lost if they can't
communicate them properly.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:33.210 align:middle line:84%
There's an old
African proverb that

00:04:33.210 --> 00:04:37.500 align:middle line:84%
says, "When an old man dies, a
library burns to the ground."

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.990 align:middle line:84%
Well, all of the experiences
you've had in your life

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:41.310 align:middle line:90%
are locked away in your head.

00:04:41.310 --> 00:04:45.960 align:middle line:84%
And only the handful who are
articulate writers or producers

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:47.880 align:middle line:84%
of scripts or works
of manuscripts

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:50.070 align:middle line:84%
that carry that
information in textbooks

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:51.900 align:middle line:90%
can get that out to people.

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:53.610 align:middle line:84%
We're reaching a
stage now where you

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:56.040 align:middle line:84%
may be able to transfer
whole blocks of experience

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:59.970 align:middle line:84%
and knowledge in a few moments
by literally opening up

00:04:59.970 --> 00:05:01.620 align:middle line:84%
channels of data
into your brain.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:04.830 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: One of the things it
says here in my notes is nature

00:05:04.830 --> 00:05:07.565 align:middle line:90%
has limited I/O.

00:05:07.565 --> 00:05:08.967 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Oh, yes, I/O--

00:05:08.967 --> 00:05:10.050 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: In-- for minds.

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:11.235 align:middle line:90%
What does that even mean?

00:05:11.235 --> 00:05:12.805 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: That's
input and output.

00:05:12.805 --> 00:05:13.605 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: OK.

00:05:13.605 --> 00:05:16.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: So what are
your primary channels?

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:19.560 align:middle line:84%
Your mouth, you
speak, your hands

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:22.500 align:middle line:84%
for communicating on a
keyboard perhaps or the works

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:24.480 align:middle line:84%
that you create with
your hands and your mind.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:27.810 align:middle line:84%
And that has really been the
rule for many, many thousands

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:28.980 align:middle line:90%
of years.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:33.330 align:middle line:84%
Recently, we found with printed
word, with recorded sound,

00:05:33.330 --> 00:05:36.720 align:middle line:84%
with video, we can transfer
a lot more experience

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:37.930 align:middle line:90%
and information.

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:40.500 align:middle line:84%
The problem is, are
we using it properly?

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:42.480 align:middle line:84%
When we get into
the bandwidth that's

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:45.420 align:middle line:84%
available by directly
tapping into the brain,

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:47.580 align:middle line:84%
we suddenly have a
wealth of experience

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:50.260 align:middle line:84%
that can be transferred
from one person to another.

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:52.020 align:middle line:84%
And recent
experiments have shown

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:54.970 align:middle line:84%
how you can actually transfer
memories or even alter or erase

00:05:54.970 --> 00:05:55.770 align:middle line:90%
memories.

00:05:55.770 --> 00:05:57.630 align:middle line:84%
All of this is an
exploration to see

00:05:57.630 --> 00:06:00.390 align:middle line:84%
how we can open up the brain
just like you can open up

00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:03.790 align:middle line:84%
the hard drive of a computer and
have full access to it without,

00:06:03.790 --> 00:06:05.700 align:middle line:84%
of course, destroying
the autonomy

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:07.425 align:middle line:90%
of the individual person.

00:06:07.425 --> 00:06:10.290 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Then you say this is
a function of nature that has

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:11.130 align:middle line:90%
limited it.

00:06:11.130 --> 00:06:15.060 align:middle line:84%
Do you believe there has been
any other kind of programming

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:16.560 align:middle line:90%
interference and so forth?

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:20.370 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, I would say
I don't see anything directly

00:06:20.370 --> 00:06:21.540 align:middle line:90%
indicated.

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:24.840 align:middle line:84%
But I do know that there
was never any real reason

00:06:24.840 --> 00:06:26.580 align:middle line:84%
to change the amount
of input and output

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:29.220 align:middle line:84%
that any brain and
any animal had.

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:30.678 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't until we
developed spoken

00:06:30.678 --> 00:06:32.845 align:middle line:84%
and then written language
that we were able to do it

00:06:32.845 --> 00:06:33.940 align:middle line:90%
in any significant way.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:36.270 align:middle line:84%
And if you think
about it, libraries

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:38.610 align:middle line:84%
were the repositories
of knowledge,

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:42.480 align:middle line:84%
and even that became
a tool of warfare.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:46.470 align:middle line:84%
The Library of Alexandria
was destroyed twice

00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:49.140 align:middle line:84%
because limiting the
knowledge and information

00:06:49.140 --> 00:06:51.120 align:middle line:90%
of a culture made them weak.

00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:53.610 align:middle line:84%
They didn't have access
to the tools of the trade.

00:06:53.610 --> 00:06:56.010 align:middle line:84%
They didn't have access to
the information they'd saved.

00:06:56.010 --> 00:06:58.560 align:middle line:84%
So it actually became
a very negative thing

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:00.510 align:middle line:84%
to be able to destroy
all their information.

00:07:00.510 --> 00:07:02.820 align:middle line:84%
Today, of course, information
is stored everywhere

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:04.240 align:middle line:90%
and is available everywhere.

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:07.920 align:middle line:84%
So the thought of losing
it all doesn't really

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:08.890 align:middle line:90%
make sense right now.

00:07:08.890 --> 00:07:11.220 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: No, it doesn't
because of the cloud.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:12.885 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Correct.

00:07:12.885 --> 00:07:15.420 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: OK, so going back,
just for a moment before we

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:20.475 align:middle line:84%
move on here and dig down
into these technologies,

00:07:20.475 --> 00:07:22.800 align:middle line:84%
the transcendental part I
talked about a moment ago.

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:24.840 align:middle line:84%
When we think of
Indigenous cultures,

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:27.840 align:middle line:84%
oftentimes they already had
more advanced technologies

00:07:27.840 --> 00:07:29.550 align:middle line:90%
mentally--

00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:32.490 align:middle line:84%
telepathy, the ability to
see beyond time and space,

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:35.500 align:middle line:84%
know when someone was coming,
remote view and all that,

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:38.560 align:middle line:84%
which really were our
innate human capacities.

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:42.240 align:middle line:84%
And it seems as though those
were actually limited and shut

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:45.525 align:middle line:84%
down as we became more
sophisticated, more educated.

00:07:45.525 --> 00:07:48.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, I think one
of the things that has to be

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:52.080 align:middle line:84%
explored is how we always talk
about five senses but we really

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:53.280 align:middle line:90%
have far more than that.

00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:54.060 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Far more, yes.

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:56.220 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Even the sensation
of being thirsty is a sense,

00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:57.270 align:middle line:90%
the sensation of balance.

00:07:57.270 --> 00:07:59.610 align:middle line:84%
The vestibular system,
that's a sense.

00:07:59.610 --> 00:08:05.430 align:middle line:84%
We have a tendency to
raise a gate against noise.

00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:07.262 align:middle line:84%
So things that we
don't fully process,

00:08:07.262 --> 00:08:08.970 align:middle line:84%
things that happen in
the background that

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:11.460 align:middle line:84%
don't seem to have
significance in the moment,

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:12.785 align:middle line:90%
we tend to ignore.

00:08:12.785 --> 00:08:14.160 align:middle line:84%
But the brain
doesn't forget them

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:16.480 align:middle line:84%
or doesn't ignore
them internally.

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:19.350 align:middle line:84%
So people who are
creative appear

00:08:19.350 --> 00:08:21.540 align:middle line:84%
to have the ability to
lower that noise threshold

00:08:21.540 --> 00:08:23.352 align:middle line:90%
and still remain functional.

00:08:23.352 --> 00:08:25.560 align:middle line:84%
Of course, they always say
that many artists are mad,

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:27.630 align:middle line:84%
but that's a matter of
opinion, I would say.

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:29.172 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: That's
a matter of-- yeah,

00:08:29.172 --> 00:08:30.935 align:middle line:90%
insanity is a matter of opinion.

00:08:30.935 --> 00:08:33.840 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: But I would say that
we have many other channels

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:37.682 align:middle line:84%
of communication besides
body language and facial--

00:08:37.682 --> 00:08:38.640 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Verbal and--

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:41.039 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: --and non-verbal
communication that we use

00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:43.260 align:middle line:84%
to transfer information
from other people.

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:46.630 align:middle line:84%
And there could be other
channels we're not aware of.

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:48.370 align:middle line:84%
I don't discount
the possibility.

00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:51.090 align:middle line:84%
I just know that what's
been most effective for us

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:54.930 align:middle line:84%
is what we're able to measure,
record, playback, see,

00:08:54.930 --> 00:08:57.735 align:middle line:90%
and share on a very clear level.

00:08:57.735 --> 00:09:00.290 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, so that's
scientific materialism for you,

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:01.090 align:middle line:90%
isn't it?

00:09:01.090 --> 00:09:02.048 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: That's true.

00:09:02.048 --> 00:09:02.880 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: OK.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:05.820 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk
about the Neuralink

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:08.700 align:middle line:84%
because we're talking
about interface with AI

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:10.420 align:middle line:84%
and its interface
with the brain.

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:12.150 align:middle line:84%
And that's the first
thing that comes up

00:09:12.150 --> 00:09:14.490 align:middle line:84%
in most people's minds
who look into this

00:09:14.490 --> 00:09:16.080 align:middle line:90%
is Elon Musk's Neuralink.

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:18.930 align:middle line:84%
And it frightens people because
they think, oh, my God, we're

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:22.083 align:middle line:84%
all going to be tethered to a
central computer and "Minority

00:09:22.083 --> 00:09:23.250 align:middle line:90%
Report" and everything else.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.000 align:middle line:84%
They're going to know
what we're thinking.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.540 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the
first place that people

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:31.320 align:middle line:90%
who are concerned about AI go.

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:34.230 align:middle line:84%
But let's talk about the
reality of what it actually

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:37.770 align:middle line:84%
is, what it's designed
to do right now compared

00:09:37.770 --> 00:09:41.075 align:middle line:84%
to what it's thought to
be used for in the future.

00:09:41.075 --> 00:09:42.000 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: All right.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:47.330 align:middle line:84%
So that is a valid
concern that we

00:09:47.330 --> 00:09:49.730 align:middle line:84%
could be vulnerable to
more sorts of attacks

00:09:49.730 --> 00:09:50.960 align:middle line:90%
we never imagined before.

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:53.630 align:middle line:84%
But primarily,
what this is about

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:57.650 align:middle line:84%
is getting information out of
the human skull that can be

00:09:57.650 --> 00:09:59.880 align:middle line:90%
used to help make life better.

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:04.880 align:middle line:84%
And so the initial studies we're
looking at movement control.

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:06.950 align:middle line:84%
And some of the
initial studies also

00:10:06.950 --> 00:10:10.190 align:middle line:84%
showed that we could predict
from the firings of groups

00:10:10.190 --> 00:10:12.590 align:middle line:84%
of neuro-cells neurons
in the brain, what

00:10:12.590 --> 00:10:14.120 align:middle line:90%
you were thinking of doing.

00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:17.390 align:middle line:84%
And this could be translated
into actual commands

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:20.900 align:middle line:84%
to move a peripheral
such as a robotic limb

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:24.230 align:middle line:84%
or play a video game
or operate a machine.

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:26.510 align:middle line:84%
And with the proper
technology, it

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:28.220 align:middle line:84%
could be routed to
a paralyzed limb

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:30.380 align:middle line:84%
so you could take
control of it once again.

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:33.920 align:middle line:84%
So it was actually done
in really the true spirit

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:37.820 align:middle line:84%
of beneficiality, making
people able to live more fully

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:39.280 align:middle line:90%
and repair damage as occurred.

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:41.870 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Wasn't it
specifically targeted for brain

00:10:41.870 --> 00:10:43.430 align:middle line:90%
injury and spinal cord injury?

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:45.290 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Yes, that's
exactly correct.

00:10:45.290 --> 00:10:47.210 align:middle line:84%
There was a lot of
work done previously

00:10:47.210 --> 00:10:50.630 align:middle line:84%
using compounds like oxytocin
and high levels of oxygen

00:10:50.630 --> 00:10:54.560 align:middle line:84%
that allowed nerve
tissue to actually heal

00:10:54.560 --> 00:10:55.855 align:middle line:90%
to a large degree.

00:10:55.855 --> 00:10:57.980 align:middle line:84%
But there are limits to
what can be done with that.

00:10:57.980 --> 00:11:01.910 align:middle line:84%
This allows you the ability
to actually bypass a missing

00:11:01.910 --> 00:11:04.040 align:middle line:90%
chunk of nerve tissue.

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:06.770 align:middle line:84%
If you can make a model
of a part of the brain

00:11:06.770 --> 00:11:09.860 align:middle line:84%
and what it's doing and you
can replicate its function,

00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:12.320 align:middle line:84%
you can then replace
that with something that

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:14.330 align:middle line:84%
isn't going to age or
wear out in the same way

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:16.580 align:middle line:90%
the brain tissue would.

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:20.330 align:middle line:84%
It's not subject to disease
or chemicals or poisons.

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:22.940 align:middle line:84%
It's something that actually
could be recorded and played

00:11:22.940 --> 00:11:25.370 align:middle line:90%
back and restructured again.

00:11:25.370 --> 00:11:28.940 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So essentially, the
brain is encouraged to reroute

00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:32.510 align:middle line:84%
that neural pathway to
another one that's functioning

00:11:32.510 --> 00:11:35.385 align:middle line:84%
to create an original healthy
effect in movement or brain

00:11:35.385 --> 00:11:36.185 align:middle line:90%
function?

00:11:36.185 --> 00:11:38.270 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, in
some cases, that's true.

00:11:38.270 --> 00:11:40.370 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes when there's
damage in the brain,

00:11:40.370 --> 00:11:43.730 align:middle line:84%
portions of the brain undergo
a process called recruitment,

00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:45.680 align:middle line:84%
where they gather
groups of neurons

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:48.860 align:middle line:84%
and retrain them to
act as surrogates

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:50.360 align:middle line:84%
for those portions
that are damaged.

00:11:50.360 --> 00:11:51.860 align:middle line:84%
And it isn't always
100% effective,

00:11:51.860 --> 00:11:52.943 align:middle line:90%
but it's certainly useful.

00:11:52.943 --> 00:11:55.220 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the brain is a
very plastic, flexible,

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:56.430 align:middle line:90%
learning machine.

00:11:56.430 --> 00:11:58.820 align:middle line:84%
But what we're looking
at now is actually

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:00.935 align:middle line:84%
getting around damaged or
missing tissue perhaps.

00:12:00.935 --> 00:12:02.960 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: The more that
recruitment part of the story.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:03.760 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Right.

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:06.560 align:middle line:84%
You can't actually recruit
tissue that doesn't exist.

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:08.810 align:middle line:84%
If you've had a tumor, for
instance, and let's say

00:12:08.810 --> 00:12:10.820 align:middle line:84%
it affected your ability
to do mathematics,

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:12.290 align:middle line:90%
and they remove that tissue.

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:14.090 align:middle line:84%
And now you're
unable to understand

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:17.052 align:middle line:84%
simple things like the number
line or what calculating is.

00:12:17.052 --> 00:12:19.010 align:middle line:84%
What if they came up with
a chip, for instance,

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.500 align:middle line:84%
that could model the
mathematical functional part

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:22.340 align:middle line:90%
of the brain?

00:12:22.340 --> 00:12:24.710 align:middle line:84%
And they implant the chip
and you spent a few weeks

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:27.170 align:middle line:90%
learning to study how it works.

00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:29.270 align:middle line:84%
You become proficient,
and pretty soon you're

00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:31.460 align:middle line:84%
calculating square roots
and numbers in your head

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:32.730 align:middle line:90%
like you never could.

00:12:32.730 --> 00:12:35.210 align:middle line:84%
But it raises a question,
are you actually thinking

00:12:35.210 --> 00:12:37.200 align:middle line:90%
about the numbers?

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:40.230 align:middle line:84%
And so for some people,
that's a tricky thing.

00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:43.550 align:middle line:84%
It's a slippery-- you can't
really decide they feel.

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:44.930 align:middle line:90%
But here's the thing.

00:12:44.930 --> 00:12:46.475 align:middle line:84%
If you're using a
calculator, are you

00:12:46.475 --> 00:12:47.600 align:middle line:90%
thinking about the numbers?

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:48.400 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Exactly.

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:51.170 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, if you have
a calculator in your head that

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:53.600 align:middle line:84%
you didn't have to touch the
buttons on and you're still

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:56.090 align:middle line:84%
understanding what the concepts
are and how they function,

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:59.206 align:middle line:84%
I'd say that you're actually
thinking about the numbers.

00:12:59.206 --> 00:13:01.680 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: You're choosing
to instruct something,

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:03.720 align:middle line:84%
so it's a choice that
you've made to engage with

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:04.115 align:middle line:90%
the numbers.

00:13:04.115 --> 00:13:04.770 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: That's right.

00:13:04.770 --> 00:13:06.728 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Even if the
calculation is happening

00:13:06.728 --> 00:13:09.420 align:middle line:84%
at lightning speed on some other
level that your natural brain

00:13:09.420 --> 00:13:10.170 align:middle line:90%
wouldn't have come up with.

00:13:10.170 --> 00:13:11.010 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Exactly.

00:13:11.010 --> 00:13:11.880 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:16.440 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, I mean, these are
all big philosophical questions

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:18.060 align:middle line:90%
that we're talking about here.

00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:20.940 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, imagine
the ability to, let's say,

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:22.500 align:middle line:90%
replace individual neurons.

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:24.840 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose we had
some nanomachine that

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:27.570 align:middle line:84%
could go into the brain,
locate damaged tissue,

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:29.907 align:middle line:84%
and build valid copies,
working copies around--

00:13:29.907 --> 00:13:32.240 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And that is what's
being worked on right now.

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:34.157 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Yeah, eventually
we'll get to that.

00:13:34.157 --> 00:13:36.900 align:middle line:84%
But what would happen if, let's
say, every neuron of the brain

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:40.440 align:middle line:84%
was slowly replaced
by a machine neuron,

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:43.320 align:middle line:84%
and over the space of, like,
10 years every one of them

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:46.922 align:middle line:84%
got replaced until you were
nothing but nanoneurons?

00:13:46.922 --> 00:13:48.255 align:middle line:90%
Well, you'd still feel the same.

00:13:48.255 --> 00:13:49.710 align:middle line:84%
You wouldn't notice
any difference.

00:13:49.710 --> 00:13:51.835 align:middle line:84%
Your memories and experiences
would still be there.

00:13:51.835 --> 00:13:53.190 align:middle line:90%
Is it you?

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:55.020 align:middle line:84%
That's a very tough
question to answer.

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:58.320 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, this is where
the esoteric part becomes very

00:13:58.320 --> 00:13:59.140 align:middle line:90%
important.

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:02.520 align:middle line:84%
And that is, those
who feel they actually

00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:05.130 align:middle line:84%
have something beyond
the meat of the brain

00:14:05.130 --> 00:14:08.220 align:middle line:84%
and those who feel they
have a spirit or soul.

00:14:08.220 --> 00:14:11.640 align:middle line:84%
In which case, if that's
permeating the brain,

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:15.450 align:middle line:84%
even if the functions have been
taken over mechanically, so

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:20.060 align:middle line:84%
to speak, how much affect
does that spirit or soul have?

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:23.020 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: And that raises a
question that actually leads

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:23.820 align:middle line:90%
to an experiment.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:25.290 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: OK, tell me.

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:27.390 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: If a part of
your brain is damaged,

00:14:27.390 --> 00:14:29.670 align:middle line:90%
does it damage your soul?

00:14:29.670 --> 00:14:32.940 align:middle line:84%
Because if it
does, then the soul

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:34.480 align:middle line:90%
is just as mutable as the brain.

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:37.830 align:middle line:84%
And if it doesn't, then
why doesn't the soul

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:40.320 align:middle line:84%
move around the function of
that missing part of the brain?

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:41.820 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Which
oftentimes it does.

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:43.722 align:middle line:90%
We call it miracles.

00:14:43.722 --> 00:14:45.930 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: There do seem to
be miracles in the world.

00:14:45.930 --> 00:14:47.560 align:middle line:90%
I can't deny that at all.

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:47.956 align:middle line:84%
I've seen some
astounding things.

00:14:47.956 --> 00:14:50.123 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah, but it's
not the most common thing.

00:14:50.123 --> 00:14:53.610 align:middle line:84%
But yes, it does exist where
for many people unaware,

00:14:53.610 --> 00:14:55.440 align:middle line:84%
they're totally
unaware even of what's

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:56.880 align:middle line:84%
breaking down and
being corrected

00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:58.978 align:middle line:90%
all the time on their behalf.

00:14:58.978 --> 00:15:01.020 align:middle line:84%
And so unless you're in
an accident and something

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:03.660 align:middle line:84%
severe like this happens,
you wouldn't know.

00:15:03.660 --> 00:15:06.390 align:middle line:84%
And then if it repairs
itself at that rate,

00:15:06.390 --> 00:15:08.370 align:middle line:84%
you're talking what
looks like a miracle when

00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:09.412 align:middle line:90%
it's just our capability.

00:15:09.412 --> 00:15:11.350 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: It's possibility.

00:15:11.350 --> 00:15:13.920 align:middle line:84%
But I think that maybe what
we're going to discover

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:16.800 align:middle line:84%
is a lot of what we think
of as the soul ends up

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:19.290 align:middle line:84%
to be the data of
your experience

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:22.350 align:middle line:84%
and the data of how
you make decisions.

00:15:22.350 --> 00:15:25.330 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, there's no
question if somebody

00:15:25.330 --> 00:15:27.228 align:middle line:84%
were to destroy your
brain you'd be gone.

00:15:27.228 --> 00:15:28.270 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: You'd be gone.

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:32.150 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Yet your soul,
your pattern of information

00:15:32.150 --> 00:15:33.985 align:middle line:84%
and existence and
everything you've done--

00:15:33.985 --> 00:15:34.860 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Continues.

00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:36.430 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: --many
would argue continues.

00:15:36.430 --> 00:15:37.390 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Absolutely.

00:15:37.390 --> 00:15:40.000 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it becomes repository
known as the subconscious,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.115 align:middle line:84%
and you get to drag it
forward if you reincarnate.

00:15:42.115 --> 00:15:44.800 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, and there's
something to think about.

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:47.980 align:middle line:84%
Everything in the universe
has an effect on spacetime,

00:15:47.980 --> 00:15:49.660 align:middle line:90%
on the vacuum itself.

00:15:49.660 --> 00:15:53.590 align:middle line:84%
Every charge, every movement,
every spin, everything does.

00:15:53.590 --> 00:15:57.130 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps what we refer to
as the soul is actually

00:15:57.130 --> 00:16:00.950 align:middle line:90%
this imprint on spacetime.

00:16:00.950 --> 00:16:02.075 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's the thought.

00:16:02.075 --> 00:16:04.085 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah, an
individuated imprint.

00:16:04.085 --> 00:16:05.040 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Could be.

00:16:05.040 --> 00:16:05.840 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:07.490 align:middle line:84%
Well, it is interesting
because that's

00:16:07.490 --> 00:16:09.530 align:middle line:84%
where the philosophical
questions really

00:16:09.530 --> 00:16:10.430 align:middle line:90%
start taking off.

00:16:10.430 --> 00:16:12.510 align:middle line:84%
We can go into all kinds
of territory with it.

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:13.310 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: True.

00:16:13.310 --> 00:16:15.435 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: But now sticking
to the terrestrial part

00:16:15.435 --> 00:16:19.400 align:middle line:84%
and the philosophical parts
over, who's running the brain?

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:23.180 align:middle line:84%
I was listening to an interview
with Elon Musk, whose company

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:24.440 align:middle line:90%
is creating the Neuralink.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:26.000 align:middle line:84%
And he says for
the next 10 years

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:30.140 align:middle line:84%
it's to be used for spinal
cord injury and brain damage.

00:16:30.140 --> 00:16:34.340 align:middle line:84%
And they're well on
their way in this now.

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:40.160 align:middle line:84%
And he said in the end, AI
is going to be so ubiquitous,

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:43.100 align:middle line:84%
you're really only going to
have a choice of the provider.

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:44.990 align:middle line:90%
And the provider which you--

00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:48.410 align:middle line:84%
you, your biggest decision
will be who is that provider?

00:16:48.410 --> 00:16:52.250 align:middle line:84%
You have to understand
what the capability to--

00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:56.490 align:middle line:84%
for input and output from
that provider so that

00:16:56.490 --> 00:16:59.220 align:middle line:84%
you don't step in a situation
in which someone else is playing

00:16:59.220 --> 00:17:00.420 align:middle line:90%
God over your own brain.

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:02.070 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Sure.

00:17:02.070 --> 00:17:05.310 align:middle line:84%
So I guess the question
is, which company do you

00:17:05.310 --> 00:17:09.449 align:middle line:84%
trust to build brain replacement
parts and not install adware.

00:17:09.449 --> 00:17:11.323 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Exactly, or malware.

00:17:11.323 --> 00:17:12.990 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: And here's
the other thought.

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:13.790 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:16.410 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: If I'm baking a
