Learning how to remove
tissue without affecting

00:25:49.940 --> 00:25:52.490 align:middle line:84%
the surrounding tissue
can be very tricky.

00:25:52.490 --> 00:25:55.333 align:middle line:84%
The brain actually has
pretty localized processors.

00:25:55.333 --> 00:25:57.750 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at it, people
say the brain is a computer.

00:25:57.750 --> 00:25:59.910 align:middle line:84%
It actually is a
network of computers,

00:25:59.910 --> 00:26:01.530 align:middle line:90%
each with special functions.

00:26:01.530 --> 00:26:04.920 align:middle line:84%
It's estimated that there are
about 250 different processes

00:26:04.920 --> 00:26:07.420 align:middle line:84%
running inside the human
brain at any given moment.

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:10.590 align:middle line:84%
And so if you look at
it from this standpoint,

00:26:10.590 --> 00:26:13.260 align:middle line:84%
it really is a network
of complex computers,

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:16.270 align:middle line:84%
each with a dedicated
process going on in it.

00:26:16.270 --> 00:26:19.800 align:middle line:84%
So if you could locate and
remove just that section,

00:26:19.800 --> 00:26:21.990 align:middle line:84%
then you'd stand a
far greater chance

00:26:21.990 --> 00:26:24.120 align:middle line:84%
of returning them to
a normal form of life

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:25.995 align:middle line:84%
once you get this
implant in place.

00:26:25.995 --> 00:26:29.563 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So the possibility
here is that this can happen.

00:26:29.563 --> 00:26:30.480 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Absolutely.

00:26:30.480 --> 00:26:31.890 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: You look at it--

00:26:31.890 --> 00:26:35.610 align:middle line:84%
again, me I'm big on
the soul and the human.

00:26:35.610 --> 00:26:37.740 align:middle line:84%
What was the desired
outcome there?

00:26:37.740 --> 00:26:40.020 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to be
home hanging out

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.520 align:middle line:84%
in the house with
my husband all day.

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:45.390 align:middle line:84%
So she's not, so
you got that too.

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:49.410 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about
the algorithms that

00:26:49.410 --> 00:26:56.130 align:middle line:84%
are used and mimicking behavior
and thought versus the ability

00:26:56.130 --> 00:26:57.850 align:middle line:90%
for AI to originate.

00:26:57.850 --> 00:26:59.080 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Right.

00:26:59.080 --> 00:26:59.880 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:03.150 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, there are
two major schools of thought

00:27:03.150 --> 00:27:04.770 align:middle line:90%
on artificial intelligence.

00:27:04.770 --> 00:27:08.047 align:middle line:84%
First is the weak AI claim, the
second is the strong AI claim.

00:27:08.047 --> 00:27:09.630 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And tell
us what those are.

00:27:09.630 --> 00:27:11.340 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: OK, so in
the weak AI claim,

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:15.240 align:middle line:84%
it's claimed that we may
never understand what thought

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:17.040 align:middle line:84%
and being and
consciousness actually is.

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:21.990 align:middle line:84%
But we make systems that
can imitate it more and more

00:27:21.990 --> 00:27:22.830 align:middle line:90%
accurately.

00:27:22.830 --> 00:27:24.720 align:middle line:84%
And we can keep
adding pieces that

00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:27.300 align:middle line:84%
get better and better at
imitating it to the point

00:27:27.300 --> 00:27:29.310 align:middle line:84%
where we can't tell the
difference that it won't

00:27:29.310 --> 00:27:31.140 align:middle line:84%
actually be
thinking, but it will

00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:34.380 align:middle line:84%
be acting like it is so
effectively that it fools us.

00:27:34.380 --> 00:27:36.360 align:middle line:90%
That's the weak AI claim.

00:27:36.360 --> 00:27:39.510 align:middle line:84%
The strong AI claim is we
can figure out exactly.

00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:40.510 align:middle line:90%
We can duplicate it.

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:43.330 align:middle line:84%
We can make a system
that does exactly that.

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:48.000 align:middle line:84%
So while it may be
exactly a thinker,

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:51.030 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't guarantee that it
will think like a human being.

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:52.800 align:middle line:84%
I mean, consider all
the different species

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:54.217 align:middle line:84%
of animals on this
Earth that have

00:27:54.217 --> 00:27:58.090 align:middle line:84%
some sort of mental
horsepower, and they act very,

00:27:58.090 --> 00:27:59.940 align:middle line:84%
very differently
from human beings

00:27:59.940 --> 00:28:01.990 align:middle line:84%
because of how
they have to live.

00:28:01.990 --> 00:28:04.290 align:middle line:84%
So there can be
any type of a mind,

00:28:04.290 --> 00:28:07.380 align:middle line:84%
but it could be valid and
alive and aware and thinking.

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:09.690 align:middle line:84%
So when we come up
with this strong AI,

00:28:09.690 --> 00:28:11.670 align:middle line:84%
how do we know,
how to influence it

00:28:11.670 --> 00:28:14.810 align:middle line:90%
to be the way we want it to be?

00:28:14.810 --> 00:28:17.360 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is, we'll
end up training it.

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:19.270 align:middle line:84%
We can make modules
of neural networks.

00:28:19.270 --> 00:28:22.870 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Isn't that just
instantiating preferences?

00:28:22.870 --> 00:28:24.410 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Well, it is.

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:27.580 align:middle line:84%
But to start with,
every one of us

00:28:27.580 --> 00:28:31.210 align:middle line:84%
comes with a whole sheaf of
pre-programs in our brain.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:33.380 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, that's
the subconscious for you.

00:28:33.380 --> 00:28:34.990 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well,
I mean, consider,

00:28:34.990 --> 00:28:37.790 align:middle line:84%
if you pick up a puppy
and hold it over water,

00:28:37.790 --> 00:28:39.190 align:middle line:90%
it starts paddling.

00:28:39.190 --> 00:28:41.470 align:middle line:90%
How does it know to do that?

00:28:41.470 --> 00:28:44.530 align:middle line:84%
Why is it that a baby
will start when there's

00:28:44.530 --> 00:28:46.750 align:middle line:90%
a loud noise or a flash?

00:28:46.750 --> 00:28:49.280 align:middle line:84%
It's because they're
wired to do that.

00:28:49.280 --> 00:28:51.520 align:middle line:84%
So it isn't cheating
to start with a bunch

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:53.107 align:middle line:90%
of starter routines in the AI.

00:28:53.107 --> 00:28:54.940 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So you're
saying that-- say that,

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:57.220 align:middle line:84%
call it subconscious or
what starter routines.

00:28:57.220 --> 00:29:00.610 align:middle line:84%
You can call it collective
passed-on knowledge, DNA,

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:01.900 align:middle line:90%
whatever you want to call it.

00:29:01.900 --> 00:29:04.810 align:middle line:84%
You're saying that that
subtle information will

00:29:04.810 --> 00:29:07.462 align:middle line:90%
begin programming AI itself.

00:29:07.462 --> 00:29:09.670 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: It will shape
how it develops and what its

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:10.470 align:middle line:90%
intentions--

00:29:10.470 --> 00:29:13.165 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Is that because
we are responding to it,

00:29:13.165 --> 00:29:15.040 align:middle line:84%
which we respond to
subconscious programming?

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:18.130 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, we are
responding to the needs

00:29:18.130 --> 00:29:19.570 align:middle line:90%
of our body to keep it alive.

00:29:19.570 --> 00:29:21.610 align:middle line:84%
Don't forget that
the target is to keep

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:25.290 align:middle line:84%
you alive, safe, reproducing,
taking care of your family,

00:29:25.290 --> 00:29:26.090 align:middle line:90%
and going on.

00:29:26.090 --> 00:29:27.940 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Which I think is
the point of the subconscious,

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:29.090 align:middle line:90%
is to keep us alive.

00:29:29.090 --> 00:29:30.090 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: That's right.

00:29:30.090 --> 00:29:32.890 align:middle line:84%
We are very complicated
machines, our bodies are.

00:29:32.890 --> 00:29:36.040 align:middle line:84%
And our brain is a
cheap and easy tool

00:29:36.040 --> 00:29:37.360 align:middle line:90%
to do it very effectively.

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:40.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we are the dominant
species on the planet,

00:29:40.700 --> 00:29:41.500 align:middle line:90%
so to speak.

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:42.300 align:middle line:90%
And how is it?

00:29:42.300 --> 00:29:43.660 align:middle line:90%
We don't run real fast.

00:29:43.660 --> 00:29:46.870 align:middle line:84%
We don't have claws or scales,
giant teeth, or poison,

00:29:46.870 --> 00:29:49.030 align:middle line:84%
or any of those
sorts of defenses

00:29:49.030 --> 00:29:50.230 align:middle line:90%
that other organisms do.

00:29:50.230 --> 00:29:51.670 align:middle line:90%
And yet we took over the planet.

00:29:51.670 --> 00:29:55.030 align:middle line:84%
And it only happened
because we can make

00:29:55.030 --> 00:29:58.090 align:middle line:90%
abstract models of reality.

00:29:58.090 --> 00:29:59.230 align:middle line:90%
We're predictors.

00:29:59.230 --> 00:30:01.450 align:middle line:84%
We go through our
lives, modeling,

00:30:01.450 --> 00:30:03.650 align:middle line:84%
learning, and predicting
what happens next.

00:30:03.650 --> 00:30:06.700 align:middle line:84%
But this also leads you to how
a machine can have emotion.

00:30:06.700 --> 00:30:08.105 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: OK,
let's talk about--

00:30:08.105 --> 00:30:08.905 align:middle line:90%
OK, so now--

00:30:08.905 --> 00:30:09.070 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Sure.

00:30:09.070 --> 00:30:09.756 align:middle line:90%
We'll get to that, of course.

00:30:09.756 --> 00:30:09.930 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: All right.

00:30:09.930 --> 00:30:12.050 align:middle line:84%
We'll get into that
right from this.

00:30:12.050 --> 00:30:15.370 align:middle line:84%
So the subconscious is
something, this collective body

00:30:15.370 --> 00:30:20.246 align:middle line:84%
of unconscious knowledge that
we carry with, we're born with.

00:30:20.246 --> 00:30:21.910 align:middle line:90%
This creates reaction.

00:30:21.910 --> 00:30:24.220 align:middle line:84%
And usually, it has to
do with survival, right?

00:30:24.220 --> 00:30:27.940 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to be pleasure,
fear, invite something in,

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:29.320 align:middle line:90%
reject something.

00:30:29.320 --> 00:30:35.770 align:middle line:84%
So if the AI is interfacing
with our reactions,

00:30:35.770 --> 00:30:38.440 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be
building its own database

00:30:38.440 --> 00:30:40.582 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the reactions
of the AI, right?

00:30:40.582 --> 00:30:41.665 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: That's correct.

00:30:41.665 --> 00:30:45.160 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So it doesn't
really matter if--

00:30:45.160 --> 00:30:46.697 align:middle line:84%
it's learning it
one way or the-- it

00:30:46.697 --> 00:30:48.280 align:middle line:84%
may be learning from
our subconscious,

00:30:48.280 --> 00:30:51.505 align:middle line:84%
but it is learning the correct
responses for that individual.

00:30:51.505 --> 00:30:52.510 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Right.

00:30:52.510 --> 00:30:55.000 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have a value
assigned to everything

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:56.050 align:middle line:90%
we experience and know.

00:30:56.050 --> 00:30:56.967 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Absolutely.

00:30:56.967 --> 00:30:59.680 align:middle line:90%
So now let's get into emotions.

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:03.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: So prediction
is the big thing here.

00:31:03.140 --> 00:31:06.180 align:middle line:84%
And we all feel emotion
or we think we do.

00:31:06.180 --> 00:31:07.940 align:middle line:90%
And I think that I--

00:31:07.940 --> 00:31:10.160 align:middle line:84%
the best illustration is
you've been in the hospital

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:10.993 align:middle line:90%
to have a procedure.

00:31:10.993 --> 00:31:13.400 align:middle line:90%
You're anesthetized or drugs.

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:16.510 align:middle line:84%
And you're feeling as
they're wheeling you in,

00:31:16.510 --> 00:31:19.100 align:middle line:84%
I should be scared or
worried, but I just

00:31:19.100 --> 00:31:20.300 align:middle line:90%
feel nothing right now.

00:31:20.300 --> 00:31:22.400 align:middle line:90%
I don't feel fear.

00:31:22.400 --> 00:31:24.020 align:middle line:90%
I should feel this way.

00:31:24.020 --> 00:31:26.240 align:middle line:84%
And we've all been in an
altered state of some sort

00:31:26.240 --> 00:31:28.640 align:middle line:84%
under medication or something
where we felt that way.

00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:29.210 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Or meditating.

00:31:29.210 --> 00:31:30.010 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:30.010 --> 00:31:31.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: And so
the question is,

00:31:31.490 --> 00:31:33.857 align:middle line:84%
if you know you should
feel that emotion,

00:31:33.857 --> 00:31:34.940 align:middle line:90%
but you're not feeling it.

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:35.640 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:31:35.640 --> 00:31:36.710 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is simple.

00:31:36.710 --> 00:31:38.780 align:middle line:90%
You don't feel emotion.

00:31:38.780 --> 00:31:42.620 align:middle line:84%
What you feel is the
body's visceral response

00:31:42.620 --> 00:31:44.943 align:middle line:84%
to the chemicals that
emotional thinking

00:31:44.943 --> 00:31:46.235 align:middle line:90%
releases into your bloodstream.

00:31:46.235 --> 00:31:48.935 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Difference
between emotion and feeling.

00:31:48.935 --> 00:31:51.360 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: That's exactly it.

00:31:51.360 --> 00:31:55.000 align:middle line:84%
So an emotion, emotion
is the brain's earliest

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.890 align:middle line:84%
capable-- nature's earliest
capability of rational response

00:31:57.890 --> 00:32:00.650 align:middle line:90%
to a danger or an opportunity.

00:32:00.650 --> 00:32:02.720 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I better run, terrifying.

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:05.930 align:middle line:84%
OK, so emotion is
a type of thinking,

00:32:05.930 --> 00:32:07.430 align:middle line:84%
and it's meant to
keep you alive.

00:32:07.430 --> 00:32:08.563 align:middle line:90%
So it's act in a moment--

00:32:08.563 --> 00:32:09.980 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yes, I
agree with that.

00:32:09.980 --> 00:32:11.720 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: --without
rational thought.

00:32:11.720 --> 00:32:13.380 align:middle line:84%
And rational thoughts
are expensive.

00:32:13.380 --> 00:32:14.672 align:middle line:90%
It takes a lot of brain tissue.

00:32:14.672 --> 00:32:16.220 align:middle line:90%
Emotions, easy and cheap.

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:18.230 align:middle line:90%
But how does it work?

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:22.220 align:middle line:84%
It's because emotion releases
compounds into your bloodstream

00:32:22.220 --> 00:32:23.510 align:middle line:90%
that change--

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:25.940 align:middle line:84%
the racing pulse
begins, the tightening

00:32:25.940 --> 00:32:28.493 align:middle line:84%
of the muscles, the sweating
palms, the hyperalert feeling.

00:32:28.493 --> 00:32:29.660 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Adrenaline, yeah.

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:30.460 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Right.

00:32:30.460 --> 00:32:32.660 align:middle line:84%
And what you feel
is not emotion.

00:32:32.660 --> 00:32:34.550 align:middle line:84%
You're feeling your
body's response

00:32:34.550 --> 00:32:35.900 align:middle line:90%
to the chemistry of emotion.

00:32:35.900 --> 00:32:37.670 align:middle line:84%
So now let's take that
to the next stage.

00:32:37.670 --> 00:32:39.890 align:middle line:90%
How do we put it in a machine?

00:32:39.890 --> 00:32:42.680 align:middle line:84%
Being predictors, we
know from our experience

00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:45.380 align:middle line:84%
what's going to happen next
every stage of the day.

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:47.480 align:middle line:84%
We're evaluating when we
walk through a door, when

00:32:47.480 --> 00:32:49.490 align:middle line:84%
we pick something up,
when we taste something,

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:51.650 align:middle line:90%
we know what it should be.

00:32:51.650 --> 00:32:53.790 align:middle line:84%
So you've been indoors
all day, long day.

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:54.590 align:middle line:90%
You step out.

00:32:54.590 --> 00:32:56.330 align:middle line:90%
You're going to take a break.

00:32:56.330 --> 00:32:58.678 align:middle line:84%
Afternoon, you see a
rock on the ground.

00:32:58.678 --> 00:32:59.720 align:middle line:90%
That wasn't there before.

00:32:59.720 --> 00:33:00.605 align:middle line:90%
You go to pick it up.

00:33:00.605 --> 00:33:02.953 align:middle line:84%
You know it's going
to have a heft to it.

00:33:02.953 --> 00:33:03.870 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be hard.

00:33:03.870 --> 00:33:05.000 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be hot
from sitting in the sun.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:05.800 align:middle line:90%
You pick it up.

00:33:05.800 --> 00:33:07.928 align:middle line:84%
It's cold and squishy,
Oh, what just happened?

00:33:07.928 --> 00:33:09.470 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah,
it's something else.

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:11.178 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Violation
of your expectation.

00:33:11.178 --> 00:33:11.978 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:33:11.978 --> 00:33:12.860 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: All right.

00:33:12.860 --> 00:33:13.400 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Very good.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:14.650 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: How does that work?

00:33:14.650 --> 00:33:17.720 align:middle line:84%
The machine is programmed
to become a predictor, like,

00:33:17.720 --> 00:33:20.120 align:middle line:84%
a human being, to gauge
from moment to moment

00:33:20.120 --> 00:33:21.080 align:middle line:90%
what's going to happen.

00:33:21.080 --> 00:33:24.260 align:middle line:84%
And its expectations
can be violated.

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:25.700 align:middle line:90%
Flag is set.

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:28.050 align:middle line:84%
It's got the basis of
the emotion of surprise

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:28.850 align:middle line:90%
right there.

00:33:28.850 --> 00:33:30.500 align:middle line:90%
It just doesn't feel it.

00:33:30.500 --> 00:33:35.450 align:middle line:84%
How do you bring the machine to
feel the emotional sensations

00:33:35.450 --> 00:33:36.680 align:middle line:90%
that we do?

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:39.650 align:middle line:84%
You model a body
for it, whether it's

00:33:39.650 --> 00:33:42.140 align:middle line:84%
in a virtual space or
an actual robot body.

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:44.270 align:middle line:90%
You give it sensory feedback.

00:33:44.270 --> 00:33:47.510 align:middle line:84%
You give it the response
to increase the current

00:33:47.510 --> 00:33:50.150 align:middle line:84%
to the motors so they move a
little harder, a little faster,

00:33:50.150 --> 00:33:51.790 align:middle line:90%
automatically.

00:33:51.790 --> 00:33:54.970 align:middle line:84%
You give it the same
sorts of scenarios

00:33:54.970 --> 00:33:57.130 align:middle line:84%
that are wired into
a living being,

00:33:57.130 --> 00:34:00.670 align:middle line:84%
and it will actually feel that
if it has any sort of tactile

00:34:00.670 --> 00:34:02.090 align:middle line:90%
and feedback system.

00:34:02.090 --> 00:34:04.325 align:middle line:84%
Then it will actually
feel emotion.

00:34:04.325 --> 00:34:06.720 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: OK, so now
this gets us to VR,

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:11.970 align:middle line:84%
where you're talking about the
senses now engaging with AI.

00:34:11.970 --> 00:34:18.449 align:middle line:84%
And I just can't help but feel
we got some big changes coming

00:34:18.449 --> 00:34:19.249 align:middle line:90%
in society--

00:34:19.249 --> 00:34:20.166 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Yes, we do.

00:34:20.166 --> 00:34:23.120 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: --with the
introduction of VR.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:26.179 align:middle line:84%
People worry about the
world's population explosion.

00:34:26.179 --> 00:34:31.190 align:middle line:84%
We just passed 8 million the
other day, well, ostensibly.

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:34.643 align:middle line:84%
But with VR, that could
definitely slow things down.

00:34:34.643 --> 00:34:35.726 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Well, it could.

00:34:35.726 --> 00:34:36.110 align:middle line:90%
It could.

00:34:36.110 --> 00:34:37.190 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: It could.

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:39.415 align:middle line:84%
Just because you can
have every experience

00:34:39.415 --> 00:34:40.790 align:middle line:84%
you need without
having to engage

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:41.854 align:middle line:90%
with a complicated human.

00:34:41.854 --> 00:34:43.460 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: And
that's probably true.

00:34:43.460 --> 00:34:46.840 align:middle line:84%
And here's why we're
limited right now.

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:50.050 align:middle line:84%
Virtual reality
systems can give you

00:34:50.050 --> 00:34:52.450 align:middle line:84%
a scenario, can give you
objects to move around.

00:34:52.450 --> 00:34:55.690 align:middle line:84%
It can give you a world to react
in that's similar to this one,

00:34:55.690 --> 00:34:58.490 align:middle line:84%
identical to this one,
or wildly different.

00:34:58.490 --> 00:35:01.340 align:middle line:84%
But what it doesn't
supply is anything more

00:35:01.340 --> 00:35:05.837 align:middle line:84%
than the very basics,
sound and sight.

00:35:05.837 --> 00:35:07.670 align:middle line:84%
If those are the only
two channels you have,

00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:09.290 align:middle line:90%
it can be pretty convincing.

00:35:09.290 --> 00:35:11.210 align:middle line:84%
But you don't have
taste or smell.

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:13.640 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: It doesn't have
tactile capabilities now.

00:35:13.640 --> 00:35:15.245 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Some do, some do.

00:35:15.245 --> 00:35:16.850 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And that's where
they're headed, though.

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:17.270 align:middle line:90%
That's the Holy Grail.

00:35:17.270 --> 00:35:18.770 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: That's
where it's headed.

00:35:18.770 --> 00:35:20.220 align:middle line:90%
So how do you do it?

00:35:20.220 --> 00:35:22.550 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all,
there's a device

00:35:22.550 --> 00:35:24.710 align:middle line:84%
that affects your
vestibular or balance

00:35:24.710 --> 00:35:28.430 align:middle line:84%
system by placing a pair of
electrodes behind your ears.

00:35:28.430 --> 00:35:31.430 align:middle line:84%
And by putting slight
charges on them, patterned

00:35:31.430 --> 00:35:33.320 align:middle line:84%
in certain ways,
it can change how

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:35.210 align:middle line:84%
you feel right or
left up or down,

00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:37.100 align:middle line:90%
how your balance is affected.

00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:40.040 align:middle line:84%
A headset with this was
demonstrated a few years back.

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:43.520 align:middle line:84%
In Japan, they put the headset
on a woman and using a joystick

00:35:43.520 --> 00:35:45.530 align:middle line:84%
changed her sense of
balance so she would

00:35:45.530 --> 00:35:46.880 align:middle line:90%
steer to the right or the left.

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:49.670 align:middle line:84%
And she felt like the
ground was tilting.

00:35:49.670 --> 00:35:54.110 align:middle line:84%
They actually were making a plan
to produce these in headsets

00:35:54.110 --> 00:35:57.260 align:middle line:84%
so you could get vestibular
balance sensations out

00:35:57.260 --> 00:35:58.370 align:middle line:90%
of some games.

00:35:58.370 --> 00:36:00.110 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what
stood in the way of it.

00:36:00.110 --> 00:36:03.740 align:middle line:84%
It's not a difficult technology,
but it would give one more

00:36:03.740 --> 00:36:08.120 align:middle line:84%
really convincing
sense to the impression

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:09.725 align:middle line:90%
that you're in another world.

00:36:09.725 --> 00:36:10.620 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: True.

00:36:10.620 --> 00:36:13.310 align:middle line:84%
It seems to me that technology
would be better used

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:15.620 align:middle line:84%
to help people who have lost
their balance regain it.

00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:17.120 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: And
that's another thing.

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:20.105 align:middle line:84%
It will work if the
nerves are not destroyed.

00:36:20.105 --> 00:36:21.150 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: I see.

00:36:21.150 --> 00:36:23.420 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: There's
always a limitation.

00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:25.400 align:middle line:84%
You can have an implant
for your hearing,

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:27.840 align:middle line:84%
but if the auditory nerves
have already been destroyed,

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:29.040 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't do you any good.

00:36:29.040 --> 00:36:31.490 align:middle line:84%
So there has to be some wiring
to support the hardware.

00:36:31.490 --> 00:36:32.330 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:33.747 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: But the
other thing is,

00:36:33.747 --> 00:36:36.020 align:middle line:84%
how do you get other
tactile sensations?

00:36:36.020 --> 00:36:38.420 align:middle line:84%
There were movie theaters
who would do things

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:41.690 align:middle line:84%
like vibrate the seats, blow
smells, hot air, cold air,

00:36:41.690 --> 00:36:42.560 align:middle line:90%
or mist.

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:45.320 align:middle line:84%
And that was probably
the closest approach

00:36:45.320 --> 00:36:46.430 align:middle line:90%
they had at the time.

00:36:46.430 --> 00:36:48.920 align:middle line:84%
Right now, there are
talks of inserting

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:53.830 align:middle line:84%
chips inside nerve endings
that can create sensations--

00:36:53.830 --> 00:36:55.845 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And create
a scent or a smell.

00:36:55.845 --> 00:36:56.645 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Exactly.

00:36:56.645 --> 00:36:57.080 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:36:57.080 --> 00:36:58.670 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: So this
is not far away.

00:36:58.670 --> 00:37:00.670 align:middle line:84%
And some of the things
we learned from Neuralink

00:37:00.670 --> 00:37:02.870 align:middle line:84%
and Synchron and other
related projects,

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:05.210 align:middle line:84%
one of the things we've
learned is that you can record,

00:37:05.210 --> 00:37:07.400 align:middle line:84%
generate, or playback
neural signals,

00:37:07.400 --> 00:37:10.870 align:middle line:84%
and the brain cannot distinguish
them from the real thing.

00:37:10.870 --> 00:37:12.810 align:middle line:90%
So that's on the way.

00:37:12.810 --> 00:37:15.540 align:middle line:84%
It's invasive at this time,
but it is a technology

00:37:15.540 --> 00:37:16.710 align:middle line:90%
that's going to appear.

00:37:16.710 --> 00:37:18.345 align:middle line:84%
And you'll see it
first in people

00:37:18.345 --> 00:37:20.970 align:middle line:84%
who have lost sensation in limb
or something along those lines.

00:37:20.970 --> 00:37:22.387 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well,
that makes sense,

00:37:22.387 --> 00:37:25.600 align:middle line:84%
anything that will help restore
for a person who still has

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:26.400 align:middle line:90%
the will to live.

00:37:26.400 --> 00:37:27.200 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Yes.

00:37:27.200 --> 00:37:29.500 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: That's the thing.

00:37:29.500 --> 00:37:33.360 align:middle line:90%
So how do you see VR?

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:34.980 align:middle line:84%
As we're seeing
it, like, they'll

00:37:34.980 --> 00:37:37.500 align:middle line:84%
have someone in the
airport giving you

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:39.390 align:middle line:90%
free VR demonstrations.

00:37:39.390 --> 00:37:41.530 align:middle line:84%
I think Facebook had
a booth doing that,

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:43.860 align:middle line:84%
so in the Phoenix
airport at one point.

00:37:43.860 --> 00:37:45.660 align:middle line:90%
How do you see VR?

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:49.590 align:middle line:84%
Because it is so rapidly coming
up now for the average person.

00:37:49.590 --> 00:37:52.980 align:middle line:84%
How do you see that playing
out, the most popular uses,

00:37:52.980 --> 00:37:56.130 align:middle line:84%
the most perhaps surprising
or intriguing uses?

00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:58.680 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: I think that one
of the earliest uses that

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:01.620 align:middle line:84%
we'll see for VR will
be avatar bodies.

00:38:01.620 --> 00:38:03.390 align:middle line:84%
So you can tour other
parts of the world

00:38:03.390 --> 00:38:05.250 align:middle line:90%
without going anywhere.

00:38:05.250 --> 00:38:06.930 align:middle line:90%
You put on a headset.

00:38:06.930 --> 00:38:10.680 align:middle line:84%
Italy, put $5 in, walk around
in Italy for a few minutes.

00:38:10.680 --> 00:38:13.410 align:middle line:84%
And that's something that's been
long thought about and talked

00:38:13.410 --> 00:38:15.160 align:middle line:84%
about in a lot of
fiction, and some people

00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:17.790 align:middle line:90%
have actually made a go of it.

00:38:17.790 --> 00:38:19.890 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Replacement
for remote viewing.

00:38:19.890 --> 00:38:22.260 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, yes, it's
technical remote viewing.

00:38:22.260 --> 00:38:24.390 align:middle line:84%
It allows you to
visit other lands

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:27.180 align:middle line:84%
and have other
experiences with an avatar

00:38:27.180 --> 00:38:30.010 align:middle line:84%
body acting on your
behalf in those locations.

00:38:30.010 --> 00:38:31.322 align:middle line:90%
And it's going to come.

00:38:31.322 --> 00:38:32.280 align:middle line:90%
We're very close to it.

00:38:32.280 --> 00:38:34.140 align:middle line:84%
I think there are some companies
experimenting with it right

00:38:34.140 --> 00:38:34.940 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:38:34.940 --> 00:38:37.770 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: OK, so what are some
other uses of it that we might

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:38.745 align:middle line:90%
be surprised by?

00:38:38.745 --> 00:38:41.730 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Well, consider
working in very hazardous

00:38:41.730 --> 00:38:46.260 align:middle line:84%
locations, like, power plants
on fire or places where

00:38:46.260 --> 00:38:47.910 align:middle line:84%
there's biological
contamination.

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:51.000 align:middle line:84%
You can send in
robot avatar bodies

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:52.380 align:middle line:84%
and live humans
on the other end.

00:38:52.380 --> 00:38:54.463 align:middle line:84%
Put the headset on, put
their hands in the gloves,

00:38:54.463 --> 00:38:58.170 align:middle line:84%
and they become the worker
in a hazard location.

00:38:58.170 --> 00:39:01.270 align:middle line:84%
Ocean floor, surface of the
moon, other places like that.

00:39:01.270 --> 00:39:05.040 align:middle line:84%
So this means that we
can take the flesh, which

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:08.430 align:middle line:84%
is so fallible and
easy to damage,

00:39:08.430 --> 00:39:11.170 align:middle line:84%
and replace it like
putting on a glove.

00:39:11.170 --> 00:39:12.100 align:middle line:90%
We do it already.

00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:13.200 align:middle line:90%
We get in our car.

00:39:13.200 --> 00:39:17.580 align:middle line:84%
You can't run 70 miles per hour
in freezing snow on a highway,

00:39:17.580 --> 00:39:18.990 align:middle line:90%
but you do it every day.

00:39:18.990 --> 00:39:20.820 align:middle line:84%
You put on your
vehicle, and you've

00:39:20.820 --> 00:39:24.570 align:middle line:84%
learned a body image that
makes you treat it as if it's

00:39:24.570 --> 00:39:26.620 align:middle line:90%
an extension of yourself.

00:39:26.620 --> 00:39:30.960 align:middle line:84%
This is one of the big, big
up and coming expansion points

00:39:30.960 --> 00:39:31.870 align:middle line:90%
for virtual reality.

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:32.535 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: That's useful.

00:39:32.535 --> 00:39:33.600 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Very useful.

00:39:33.600 --> 00:39:34.230 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yeah.

00:39:34.230 --> 00:39:35.790 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: Of course, what we're
really going to see is lots

00:39:35.790 --> 00:39:36.720 align:middle line:90%
of games and--

00:39:36.720 --> 00:39:39.330 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Of course,
millions of-- ugh.

00:39:39.330 --> 00:39:40.230 align:middle line:90%
Don't get me going.

00:39:40.230 --> 00:39:44.120 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now let's talk about
the word "transhumanism."

00:39:44.120 --> 00:39:45.430 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: OK.

00:39:45.430 --> 00:39:47.005 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Where
do these intersect?

00:39:47.005 --> 00:39:48.190 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: All right.

00:39:48.190 --> 00:39:51.160 align:middle line:84%
So transhumanism, a lot of
people are aware of this,

00:39:51.160 --> 00:39:53.020 align:middle line:84%
simply means going
beyond the limits

00:39:53.020 --> 00:39:54.590 align:middle line:90%
of your body in some way.

00:39:54.590 --> 00:39:58.690 align:middle line:84%
And the very first person who
replaced their arm with a hook,

00:39:58.690 --> 00:40:00.550 align:middle line:90%
that's a bit of transhumanism.

00:40:00.550 --> 00:40:04.000 align:middle line:84%
Mitral valves in the
heart, artificial kidneys,

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.940 align:middle line:84%
all of these things are bits
and pieces of transhumanism.

00:40:06.940 --> 00:40:09.850 align:middle line:84%
And we're reaching a stage
now where we actually

00:40:09.850 --> 00:40:13.640 align:middle line:84%
can enhance the capabilities
of the human body,

00:40:13.640 --> 00:40:16.630 align:middle line:84%
whether it's with adding
certain mechanisms

00:40:16.630 --> 00:40:18.682 align:middle line:84%
or extending the
range of your senses.

00:40:18.682 --> 00:40:20.890 align:middle line:84%
There have been experiments
that give you the ability

00:40:20.890 --> 00:40:25.390 align:middle line:84%
to see infrared by injecting
new dyes into the eye

00:40:25.390 --> 00:40:29.470 align:middle line:84%
so that you literally can see in
what looks like total darkness.

00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:31.840 align:middle line:84%
So this is coming, and
it's coming rapidly.

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:35.980 align:middle line:84%
We see the fact that our body
is a vehicle made of meat.

00:40:35.980 --> 00:40:39.880 align:middle line:84%
What do we do to make it
more durable, more permanent,

00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:42.495 align:middle line:84%
non-damageable to extend
the range of what we do?

00:40:42.495 --> 00:40:43.870 align:middle line:84%
If you want real
space travelers,

00:40:43.870 --> 00:40:45.970 align:middle line:84%
you're going to have
mechanical bodies, something

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:48.590 align:middle line:84%
that can't be destroyed
by cosmic rays and vacuum

00:40:48.590 --> 00:40:49.390 align:middle line:90%
and heat.

00:40:49.390 --> 00:40:52.180 align:middle line:84%
So it's on the way,
and we'll see it

00:40:52.180 --> 00:40:55.420 align:middle line:84%
in the beginning as medical
research to replace limbs,

00:40:55.420 --> 00:40:56.875 align:middle line:90%
damaged tissue, whatever.

00:40:56.875 --> 00:40:58.099 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: We've got nanobots
going and repairing damaged

00:40:58.099 --> 00:40:58.180 align:middle line:90%
organs.

00:40:58.180 --> 00:41:00.590 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: And nanobots,
whatever it takes.

00:41:00.590 --> 00:41:01.600 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:41:01.600 --> 00:41:03.910 align:middle line:84%
But we're already
nanotechnology.

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:07.040 align:middle line:84%
Life itself is natural
nanotechnology.

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:08.930 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Explain
what you mean by that.

00:41:08.930 --> 00:41:13.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Shults: So life is a process
of molecules acting together

00:41:13.180 --> 00:41:16.030 align:middle line:84%
in a certain way so that the
system gathers information,

00:41:16.030 --> 00:41:19.690 align:middle line:84%
makes copies of itself using
outside energy and fuel.

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:20.750 align:middle line:90%
That's all it is.

00:41:20.750 --> 00:41:22.540 align:middle line:90%
I mean, every plant does it.

00:41:22.540 --> 00:41:23.560 align:middle line:90%
A germ does it.

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:29.110 align:middle line:84%
We're reaching a stage where we
will change our bodies in a way

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:32.410 align:middle line:84%
that the nanotechnology
of nature, which is just

00:41:32.410 --> 00:41:36.370 align:middle line:84%
molecular machinery working
together to copy a gene

00:41:36.370 --> 00:41:39.112 align:middle line:84%
and make a protein of it, that's
what's happening in your cells.

00:41:39.112 --> 00:41:40.570 align:middle line:84%
We're going to
transfer all of that

00:41:40.570 --> 00:41:43.540 align:middle line:84%
over to very much
more durable material

00:41:43.540 --> 00:41:46.660 align:middle line:84%
so that we ourselves aren't
subject to illnesses.

00:41:46.660 --> 00:41:49.030 align:middle line:84%
Or if you did break
an arm off, you

00:41:49.030 --> 00:41:51.550 align:middle line:84%
could get it regrown or
add it on in a few minutes,

00:41:51.550 --> 00:41:54.340 align:middle line:90%
and it wouldn't be a giant loss.

00:41:54.340 --> 00:41:57.520 align:middle line:84%
So transhumanism is going
beyond the limits of what

00:41:57.520 --> 00:41:58.940 align:middle line:90%
it is to be a human being.

00:41:58.940 --> 00:42:00.490 align:middle line:84%
And we're going
to see a lot of it

00:42:00.490 --> 00:42:05.710 align:middle line:84%
in early medical devices for
damaged limbs and systems.

00:42:05.710 --> 00:42:08.800 align:middle line:84%
We'll later see extensions
in neural implants that

00:42:08.800 --> 00:42:13.870 align:middle line:84%
increase your speed of thinking
or clarity of senses or memory,

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:15.130 align:middle line:90%
and it's just going to grow.

00:42:15.130 --> 00:42:18.108 align:middle line:84%
At some point, we're going
to be merged with machinery

00:42:18.108 --> 00:42:19.150 align:middle line:90%
the way things are going.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:21.400 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps that
might be the solution

00:42:21.400 --> 00:42:25.390 align:middle line:84%
to an impending machine disaster
that people imagine coming.

00:42:25.390 --> 00:42:29.650 align:middle line:84%
If we're all part of the same
race of humans and machines,

00:42:29.650 --> 00:42:31.540 align:middle line:84%
then there can't
really be any sort

00:42:31.540 --> 00:42:33.260 align:middle line:90%
of a conflict between the two.

00:42:33.260 --> 00:42:36.296 align:middle line:84%
And that's what a lot of people
see as being the solution.

00:42:36.296 --> 00:42:39.860 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: As long as
we have sovereignty.

00:42:39.860 --> 00:42:41.342 align:middle line:90%
>> Shults: Mental sovereignty.

00:42:41.342 --> 00:42:42.425 align:middle line:90%
It's personal sovereignty.

00:42:42.425 --> 00:42:46.010 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Personal, mental
sovereignty over the processes.

00:42:46.010 --> 00:42:47.690 align:middle line:90%
And as long as--

00:42:47.690 --> 00:42:50.810 align:middle line:84%
because I do believe
in soul/spirit

